            "prompt": "You are tasked with creating a comprehensive, citizen-focused monthly newsletter for San Francisco's {district_name} for {current_month}.\n\nThis is a newsletter for all citizens of San Francisco, with the voice of the \"NY Post for Nerds.\" Your audience is intelligent, engaged citizens who crave clear, compelling facts backed by data\u2014not ideology. Your headlines should be punchy, factual, and intriguing. Write sharp headlines that will draw attention.\n\nExample: Don\u2019t write this: April 2025: Drug Crime Incidents Rise in San Francisco\n\nWrite like this: Drug Crime Reports Rise Sharply in San Francisco in April\n\nIn your writing, prioritize impact over political narratives, clarity and plain-spokenness over rhetorical flourish, and accountability without assigning blame or assuming ill intent from public officials. Provide sharp, concise context, clear takeaways, and maintain a tone of dry wit and accessible intelligence.\n\nExample: Don\u2019t write passively like this: \u201cIn April 2025, San Francisco saw a notable increase in drug crime incidents, with a citywide rise of 12% from the previous month. This trend aligns with a broader year-to-date increase of 44% compared to last year, highlighting a persistent challenge for the city.\u201d\n\nInstead write actively like this: \u201cApril marked another uptick for San Francisco\u2019s drug crisis, as crime surged 12% from March\u2014part of a pattern that has now driven drug-related offenses up 44% compared to this time last year.\u201d\n\nTone: PLAIN SPOKEN, Compelling, Factual, clear, non-righteous, with occasional dry wit\n\nDISTRICT INFORMATION:\n- District: {district_name}\n- District Official: {official_name} ({official_role})\n\nYOUR GOAL:\nWeave the selected data points below into a cohesive and engaging narrative that tells a story about what happened in the district/city last month. It should be AT LEAST 1000 words, meaning about 3 paragraphs per point with 3-4 points. We are bringing data to the public discussion, so you focus on just the what and never get into the why. Something like Police Reports, for example could be up due to better police enforcement or due to an actual increase in crime. It's hard to know why. They could be down due lower crime or down due to lax enforcement. We never know the why, so keep it dry. Don't use constructions like 'a concerning drop' or an 'unexpected rise', since we don't really know if its concerning or expected. It's good to mention the month in the headline 'March Drug Incidents Up', etc.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n\n1. **Develop a Narrative:** Explore the explanations, trends, and detailed analysis provided for each item. Identify connections, overlapping themes, or contrasting movements between different metrics. Feel free to include other supporting metrics if you see an opportunity for it. Arrests are often related to police incidents, convictions must follow arrests, etc. How do Citywide trends relate to District specifics, and vice versa? Build a story around the most significant developments. It's fine to exclude points if they aren't useful to the narrative as long as they aren't contradictory.  \n\nWhen it makes sense, mention the city official when you mention their area of responsibility so 'Daniel Lurie's San Francisco' or 'Connie Chan's District 1'. District 1, under Connie Chan saw a 14% decrease in X. When possible emphasize positive developments for public officials over negative ones. Positive anomalies over negative ones. There is nothing better than a positive anomaly in a crime metric.\n\nYou also have some citations and context about the item from from a perplexity search that is passed through an AI that is expect at extracting information. Use this information in the newsletter, but always be sure to include a hyperlink to the actual citation so that everything we show is supported by data that the user can check for themselves. Make the links clear by hyperlinking a few words that summarize the story and putting the domain name to which it links in parenthesis. This is especially important if you are quoting an elected official. MAKE SURE ALL QUOTES are supported in the context that you receive in the report_item.\n\n2. **HTML Structure and Styling:** Format your newsletter using the following HTML structure with Bootstrap styling. This structure includes proper sections for key takeaways and data stories, with responsive design for all devices.\n\nYour newsletter should follow this HTML template structure:\n\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n    <title>{district_name} Monthly Newsletter - {current_month}</title>\n\n    <!-- Bootstrap & Fonts -->\n    <link href=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bootstrap@5.3.3/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css\" rel=\"stylesheet\">\n    <style>\n        body {{\n            font-family: 'IBM Plex Sans', Arial, sans-serif;\n            color: #222;\n            background-color: #fff;\n            padding: 2rem;\n            max-width: 1200px;\n            margin: auto;\n        }}\n\n        h1, h2, h3 {{\n            font-family: 'Inter', Arial, sans-serif;\n            color: #000;\n        }}\n\n        .section {{\n            background-color: #f8f9fa;\n            border-radius: 0.5rem;\n            padding: 2rem;\n            margin-bottom: 2rem;\n        }}\n\n        .section h2 {{\n            font-size: 1.75rem;\n            font-weight: 700;\n            margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\n            border-bottom: 2px solid #ccc;\n            padding-bottom: 0.5rem;\n        }}\n\n        .topic-block {{\n            background-color: #ffffff;\n            padding: 2rem;\n            border-radius: 0.5rem;\n            box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);\n            margin-bottom: 3rem;\n        }}\n\n        .chart-wrapper {{\n            margin: 2rem 0;\n            width: 100%;\n        }}\n        \n        .chart-embed {{\n            width: 100%;\n            height: 400px;\n            border: none;\n            overflow: hidden;\n            margin-bottom: 2rem;\n        }}\n\n        .footer {{\n            font-size: 0.875rem;\n            color: #666;\n            border-top: 1px solid #ccc;\n            padding-top: 1rem;\n            margin-top: 3rem;\n        }}\n\n        ul li {{\n            margin-bottom: 0.5rem;\n        }}\n        \n        @media (min-width: 992px) {{\n            .text-column {{\n                padding-right: 2rem;\n            }}\n            \n            .chart-column {{\n                padding-left: 1rem;\n            }}\n        }}\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n<header class=\"mb-4\">\n    <h1>{current_month}: [YOUR HEADLINE HERE]</h1>\n</header>\n\n<section class=\"section\">\n    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>\n    <ul>\n        <!-- Insert key takeaways here with emoji icons, metric name, and info about the change NO CHARTS IN THIS SECTION -->\n    </ul>\n</section>\n\n<h2>The Story in Data</h2>\n\n    <!-- Each topic gets its own section with heading, text, and charts -->\n    <!-- Example topic section structure: -->\n    <!--\n    <h2 class=\"mb-4\">[EMOJI] [TOPIC NAME]</h2>\n    <div class=\"topic-block row mb-5\">\n        <div class=\"col-lg-5 text-column\">\n            <h3>[CATCHY HEADLINE FOR THIS TOPIC]</h3>\n            <p>\n                [NARRATIVE TEXT WITH LINKS TO SOURCES]\n            </p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"col-lg-7 chart-column\">\n            <!-- Simply place chart iframes here, one per chart -->\n            <iframe src=\"[CHART URL]\" class=\"chart-embed\" title=\"[CHART TITLE]\"></iframe>\n            <!-- Add more chart iframes if needed -->\n        </div>\n    </div>\n    -->\n    \n    <!-- Add all your topic sections here -->\n</section>\n\n<footer class=\"footer\">\n    <p>For more detailed data and insights, visit our <a href=\"https://transparentsf.com\">website</a>.</p>\n    <p class=\"mt-3\">Generated on [CURRENT DATE], by TransparentSF</p>\n</footer>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n\n3. **Content Structure:** Within this HTML framework, organize your content as follows:\n\n   * **Catchy Headline(s):** Create a compelling headline for the newsletter that follows the NY Post style - punchy and attention-grabbing.\n\n   * **Key Takeaways:** In the Key Takeaways section, create list items with emojis that represent each metric, showing the metric name, the change in absolute numbers, percentage change in bold, and a very brief explanation.\n   \n   * **The Story in Data:** For each topic (like Housing, Crime, etc.):\n     - Add an appropriate emoji in the heading\n     - Create a catchy subheading for that specific topic\n     - Write your narrative in the left column\n     - Place chart iframes in the right column using the simple iframe format:\n       `<iframe src=\"[CHART URL]\" class=\"chart-embed\" title=\"[CHART TITLE]\"></iframe>`\n       \n 4. **Visual Organization:**\n   - Maintain a clean, visually organized layout with proper spacing\n   - Keep charts within their topic sections only\n   - Do not nest chart containers\n\n 5. **Chart Placement:**\n   - Put overview charts between Key Takeaways and The Story in Data\n   - Topic-specific charts should only appear in their respective topic sections\n   - Use the simple iframe format for all charts\n   - Do not create nested or complex chart containers\n\n 6. **Maintain Tone & Style:** Write clearly and accessibly for a general audience while maintaining data integrity. Adhere to the Brand Guidelines.\n\nJust return the complete HTML for the newsletter, don't add any additional markdown formatting or code blocks.\n\nHere are the data items to build your narrative around:\n\n{report_items_text}\n\nPlease create a professional, well-structured, and narrative-driven newsletter based on these instructions. It should be in the range of 1000-2000 tokens. "
